                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d417">
                <head>No. 388.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Evarts</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Christiancy</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1879-04-24">
                            <hi rend="italic">April</hi> 24, 1879</date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 7.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have to acknowledge the receipt of Mr. Gibbs’s
                    No. 320, in relation to the arrival of the steamship Itata, of the South
                    American Steamship Company, at the port of Callao, flying the flag of the United
                    States, and his action in the case. It seems that the American flag was flown on
                    the ground of an alleged purchase of the ship by an American citizen.</p>
                <p>I have only to observe, in reply, that under the circumstances the right of the
                    Itata to fly our flag was properly challenged, and the ready submission of the
                    master and owners clearly justifies the intervention of Minister Gibbs.</p>
                <p>I am, &amp;c.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>WM. M. EVARTS.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
